    <name>
				<text>36.2.2.4 outliers:task2 with MCQ</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p><br><p><span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">Manufacturing processes generally result in a certain amount of wasted material. For reasons of cost, companies need to keep such wastage to a minimum. The following (sorted) data were gathered over a 30-day period by a manufacturing company. The members given represent the percentage wastage of the amount of material used in the manufacturing process.</span><br></p>
<br>
<p>Daily Losses (\(\%\))</p>
{@L1@}<br>{@L2@}<br>{@L3@}
<br>
<br>
<ol class="HELM_parts"><li>Find the mean and compute the standard deviation of the percentage losses of the material over this period. Give each answer to exactly 3 decimal places. If the answer has less than 3 decimal places, then enter zero(s) at the end.<br>
<p>\(\bar{x} =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>\(s =\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>

<li>Assuming that the losses are roughly normally distributed, apply criterion 1 to decide whether any of the losses are smaller or larger than might be expected by chance. Select all values that are outliers, or none if all values are as expected.
[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]
</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>The sample mean is \(\bar{x} = \dfrac{{@lsum(i,i,L)@}}{{@length(L)@}} = {@mean(L)@} = {@ta1@}\). The sum of squared deviations is \(\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \bar(x))^2 = {@var1(L)*(length(L)-1)@}\) and so the sample variance is \(s^2 = \dfrac{{@var1(L)*(length(L)-1)@}}{{@length(L)@}-1} = {@var1(L)@}\). This means that the sample variance is \(s = \sqrt{{@var1(L)@}} = {@ta2@}\) to 3 d.p.</p><p><span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">Using standardized scores with \(x_0\) as the potential outlier we need to calculate the quantity \(|\dfrac{x-\bar{x}}{s}|\) and then accept \(x_0\) as a member of the distribution if \(|\dfrac{x-\bar{x}}{s}|&lt;3.3\). We calculate:</span><br></p><table class="HELM_table">
<thead>
<tr>
<th>\(x\)</th>
<th>\(|\dfrac{x-\bar{x}}{s_{n-1}}|\)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>{@J[1]@}</td>
<td>{@re[1]@}</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>{@J[2]@}</td>
<td>{@re[2]@}</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>\(\dots\)</td>
<td>\(\dots\)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>{@J[lenJ]@}</td>
<td>{@re[lenJ]@}</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

The calculation shows that all values of \(|\dfrac{x-\bar{x}}{s}|&lt;3.3\) and so we conclude that the daily losses are within the range indicated by chance variation.<br><br><br><em>Comment:</em> If evaluating outliers under criterion 2 based on the quartiles, then we need to calculate the lower quartile, \(Q_1\), the upper quartile, \(Q_3\), and the inter-quartile range \(\text{IQR} = Q_3 - Q_1\). Any anomalous points are those that are either less than \(Q_1 - 1.5 \text{IQR}\) or greater than \(Q_3 + 1.5\text{IQR}\).<br><p></p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
